{"parse":{"title":"Decadentism","pageid":9633995,"revid":754331268,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Decadentism</b> (also called <b>Decadentismo</b>) was an Italian artistic style based mainly on the <a href=\"/wiki/Decadent_movement\" title=\"Decadent movement\">Decadent movement</a> in the arts in France and England around the end of the 19th century.  The main authors associated with decadentism were <a href=\"/wiki/Antonio_Fogazzaro\" title=\"Antonio Fogazzaro\">Antonio Fogazzaro</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Italo_Svevo\" title=\"Italo Svevo\">Italo Svevo</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Giovanni_Pascoli\" title=\"Giovanni Pascoli\">Giovanni Pascoli</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Gabriele_D%27Annunzio\" title=\"Gabriele D&#39;Annunzio\">Gabriele D'Annunzio</a>.  Although differing stylistically, they championed idiosyncrasy and irrationality against scientific rationalism.  A later critic, <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Walter_Binni&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Walter Binni (page does not exist)\">Walter Binni</a>, analyzed the style favorably in his 1936 book <i>La poetica del decadentismo</i> and distinguished between moral and aesthetic decadence.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  Another scholar of decadentism was <a href=\"/wiki/Norberto_Bobbio\" title=\"Norberto Bobbio\">Norberto Bobbio</a>, noted especially for his 1945 book, <i>La filosofia del decadentismo</i>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Decadentism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Decadent_movement\" title=\"Decadent movement\">Decadent movement</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Decadentism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Drake, Richard (1982). \"Decadence, Decadentism, and Decadent Romanticism in Italy: Toward a Theory of <i>D\u00e9cadence</i>\". <i>Journal of Contemporary History</i>. <b>17</b>: 69\u201392. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1177/002200948201700104\">10.1177/002200948201700104</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Contemporary+History&amp;rft.atitle=Decadence%2C+Decadentism%2C+and+Decadent+Romanticism+in+Italy%3A+Toward+a+Theory+of+D%C3%A9cadence&amp;rft.volume=17&amp;rft.pages=69-92&amp;rft.date=1982&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1177%2F002200948201700104&amp;rft.aulast=Drake&amp;rft.aufirst=Richard&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADecadentism\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:P_literature.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/P_literature.svg/30px-P_literature.svg.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"27\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/P_literature.svg/45px-P_literature.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/P_literature.s